Pick the @tarragon{3%sprigs} leaves from the sprigs and finely chop them. Dissolve the @chicken stock pot{1} in the @boiling water{200%ml}.

Cut the @leek{4} in half lengthways then cut very thinly widthways (i.e. shred it). Remove any traces of fat from the @pork medallions{4}. Season on both sides with a good sprinkle of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Boil your #kettle{} and use the water to fill a large #saucepan{}. Chop the @new potatoes{2} in half and add them to the boiling water with a pinch of salt. Cook until you can easily slip a knife through them (~{12%minutes}). Drain and keep to the side.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over high heat. Stir-fry your leek in batches for about ~{4%minutes} with a pinch of salt. Remove from the pan as soon as it is soft enough to eat and cover to keep warm.

In the same frying pan, add another splash of @oil{}. Brown each medallion on both sides for ~{2%minutes} (turning only once).

> Tip: Cook in batches if necessary if you only have a small pan. By not overcrowding the pan you can brown the pork rather than stew it.

Once your pork is brown, pour in the stock. Add your chopped tarragon leaves. Stir well to get any meaty bits from the bottom of the pan. Simmer gently to reduce the liquid by a third.

Turn the heat to low, add the @sour cream{1} and stir.

> Tip: Make sure the sauce does not boil as this could curdle your sour cream.

Allow everything to warm through for a few mins.

> Tip: Your pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle. Test for seasoning and add more salt and pepper if needed.

Serve your potatoes onto a #plate{} with your leek on top. Place your pork medallion on top of your leek and pour over your sauce. Et voila!